Finance Crisis in 2016 Project¶

  1. This Capstone Project is specially designed for Hacctech's Data Science with Python program (DSP2105) serving the purpose of examining how great the student is in terms of mastering the Data Analytics, such that laying a solid foundation for future careers.

1- Project background¶

In this data project we will focus on exploratory data analysis (EDA) of stock prices of some banks.

We'll focus on bank stocks and see how they progressed throughout the financial crisis all the way to early 2016.

2- Install packages in Anaconda¶

We assume you have installed those regular packages in Anaconda, such as numpy, scipy, pandas, matplotlib, seaborn, etc. but the special packages for stock prices, "pandas_datareader" and "cufflinks" libraries, may not be installed in Anaconda by default.

  1. Install pandas_datareader package
  • Open "Anaconda Navigator", click "Environments", select "base (root)";
  • Type in "pandas_datareader" in the "Search Packages" box while ensuring Channels stay at "All" or "Not Installed";
  • Check the box of "pandas_datareader" and click "Apply" to install.
  1. Install cufflinks package
  • Open "Anaconda Prompt";

  • Type in the following command to install cufflinks:

    conda install -c conda-forge cufflinks-py

  • Type in "Y" or "yes" when prompted.

Data¶

We need to get data using pandas_datareader. And we will get stock information for the following banks:

  • Bank of America
  • CitiGroup
  • Goldman Sachs
  • JPMorgan Chase
  • Morgan Stanley
  • Wells Fargo

Figuring out how to get the stock data from Jan 1st 2006 to Jan 1st 2016 for each of these banks. Setting each bank to be a separate dataframe, with the variable name for that bank being its ticker symbol. This involved a few steps:

  1. Use datetime to set start and end datetime objects.
  2. Figure out the ticker symbol for each bank.
  3. Figure out how to use pandas_datareader to grab info on the stock.

Use this documentation page for hints and instructions.

# Bank of America
BAC = data.DataReader("BAC", 'google', start, end)

Creating a new empty DataFrame called `returns`. This dataframe will contain the returns for each bank's stock. `returns` are typically defined by:

$$r_t = \frac{p_t - p_{t-1}}{p_{t-1}} = \frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}} - 1$$
In [13]:
returns = pd.DataFrame()

Using pandas pct_change() method on the Close column to create a column representing this return value. Creating a for loop that goes and for each Bank Stock Ticker creates this returns column and set's it as a column in the returns DataFrame.

8- More cufflinks Plotting¶

In this part of the project, We will rely on the cufflinks library to create some Technical Analysis plots. This part of the project is experimental due to its heavy reliance on the cuffinks project.

Using `.iplot(kind='candle')` to create a candle plot of Bank of America's stock from Jan 1st 2015 to Jan 1st 2016.

In [36]:
bac15 = BAC[['Open','High','Low','Close']].loc['2015-01-01':'2016-01-01']
bac15.iplot(kind = 'candle')

Using `.ta_plot(study='sma')` to create a `Simple Moving Averages` plot of Morgan Stanley for the year 2015.

In [37]:
MS['Close'].loc['2015-01-01':'2016-01-01'].ta_plot(study = 'sma', periods =[13,21,55])

Using `.ta_plot(study='boll')` to create a `Bollinger Band` Plot for Bank of America for the year 2015.

In [38]:
